SIMPLE: iota
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Iota
<hw>I*o"ta</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L., fr. Gr.
<grk>'iw^ta</grk>. See <er>Jot</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The ninth letter of the Greek alphabet (⟦iota⟧)
corresponding with the English <it>i</it>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <ety>[from iota being the smallest letter in the Greek
alphabet.]</ety> <def>A very small quantity or degree; a jot; a
particle.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><q>They never depart an <qex>iota</qex> from the authentic formulas
of tyranny and usurpation.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Iota subscript</b></col> <fld>(Gr. Gram.)</fld>, <cd>iota
written beneath a preceding vowel, as <grk>a,</grk>, <grk>h,</grk>,
<grk>w,</grk>, -- done when iota is silent.</cd></cs><-- we use a
following comma to represent the iota subscript within Greek
transcriptions. See the "webfont.asc" file for complete description of
Greek transliterations. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Iotacism</ent>⟦br⟧
